WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.990
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:16.100 --> 00:00:17.400
&gt;&gt; Stephanie Marcus:
I'm Stephanie Marcus

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:19.840
from the Science, Technology
and Business Division.

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:26.030
I think it was appropriate that
we had a mini derecho last night

00:00:26.030 --> 00:00:30.330
in advance of our talk on water.

00:00:30.330 --> 00:00:34.520
Today we're going to not look
into outer space, as we often do

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:38.140
in these lectures, but we're
going to look at our own planet,

00:00:38.140 --> 00:00:41.780
and learn how NASA is using
satellite observations

00:00:41.780 --> 00:00:48.100
to monitor water and its
sustainability and security.

00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:51.000
And we're lucky today
to have Dr. John Bolten

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:52.490
from NASA Goddard.

00:00:52.490 --> 00:00:56.090
And I will have to read his
title, because they always have

00:00:56.090 --> 00:00:57.500
so many titles at NASA.

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:00.900
But for today he is the
Associate Program Manager

00:01:00.900 --> 00:01:05.150
of Water Resources for the
NASA Applied Sciences Program.

00:01:05.150 --> 00:01:09.230
Dr. Bolten's background is
in geology, with an emphasis

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:11.850
on hydrology and remote sensing.

00:01:11.850 --> 00:01:15.510
So please help me welcome
Dr. Bolten to the Library.

00:01:15.510 --> 00:01:19.180
[ Applause ]

00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:20.480
&gt;&gt; John Bolten: Thank
you so much.

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:21.780
And thank you everyone
for coming

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:23.210
and spending an hour
with me today.

00:01:23.210 --> 00:01:24.960
It's quite an honor to be here.

00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:28.940
So today I'm going to be
telling a bit of a story

00:01:28.940 --> 00:01:31.540
about Earth science,
and what NASA does.

00:01:31.540 --> 00:01:33.670
We have a lot of
activities that are focused

00:01:33.670 --> 00:01:38.000
on observing the earth, and
using all these fancy tools

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.990
and technology that's
being developed at NASA

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:43.230
for observing the earth.

00:01:43.230 --> 00:01:45.090
And my focus today
will be on water,

00:01:45.090 --> 00:01:49.000
and how we use observations from
satellite, numerical modeling

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.340
for water security and
global water sustainability.

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:55.710
So a quick background.

00:01:55.710 --> 00:01:58.600
A lot of people say, "What is
NASA doing with Earth science?"

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:00.390
In fact, we do quite a bit

00:02:00.390 --> 00:02:04.320
of Earth-science-focused
research and applications.

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:08.050
In the NASA Applied Sciences
Program the mission statement is

00:02:08.050 --> 00:02:11.950
to provide innovative
solutions of applications

00:02:11.950 --> 00:02:14.870
of NASA satellites
and numerical modeling

00:02:14.870 --> 00:02:17.510
for improving decision making.

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:20.980
And we work with a lot of
institutions around the world

00:02:20.980 --> 00:02:22.890
for improving their
decision making,

00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:26.370
and also integrating these
solutions into their policies

00:02:26.370 --> 00:02:29.060
and their business solutions.

00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:31.590
So let's take this.

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:33.130
Does anyone know what this is?

00:02:33.130 --> 00:02:34.430
Does that look familiar?

00:02:34.430 --> 00:02:35.730
This is a quiz.

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:39.590
It's a current event,
this, in the news a lot.

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:42.600
What this is is actually
a cattle farm.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:45.140
Okay? And you're seeing
the cattle farm surrounded

00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:47.800
by agricultural fields.

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:49.100
So why is this relevant?

00:02:49.100 --> 00:02:50.400
Why is this important?

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:54.410
Well, we've heard about
the recent E.coli outbreak.

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:57.410
Now in a cattle farm if
there's too much moisture

00:02:57.410 --> 00:03:01.140
in the soil, it breeds disease.

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:03.880
And if there's too
little, it leads to dust.

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:07.580
And that dust can carry
bacteria, including E.coli.

00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:10.590
And it can spread to
the surrounding fields.

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:14.260
So this is one quick example

00:03:14.260 --> 00:03:18.680
of how Earth science can be
applied, and is contributing

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:22.710
to our better understanding
of our world in recent events.

00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:24.060
Here's another recent event.

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:26.650
This is in Cape Town,
South Africa.

00:03:26.650 --> 00:03:30.890
So you may have heard of
Cape Town's recent struggle

00:03:30.890 --> 00:03:32.190
with water.

00:03:32.190 --> 00:03:34.710
So they actually have
something they call "Zero Day."

00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:37.910
This is the day that Cape
Town will run out of water.

00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:42.050
And this is an unprecedented
event where a town, Cape Town,

00:03:42.050 --> 00:03:46.190
I think the population is
roughly half a million people.

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:48.360
And they expect to
run out of water.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.760
Initially it was going
to be in June 2018.

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:54.820
And they've moved it
forward a bit to 2019.

00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:58.180
So there's a lot of
focus on Cape Town.

00:03:58.180 --> 00:04:00.020
I'll come back to this.

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:01.320
But it's a really good example.

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:04.410
So within water you don't
want to have too little of it,

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:06.060
you don't want to
have too much of it.

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:09.010
Right? And that's what
I'll be talking about.

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:10.310
