00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:30.070
&gt;&gt; John Bolten: So that was
an attention-grabbing video.

00:05:30.070 --> 00:05:33.270
But this happened a mile from
my house in Ellicott City.

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:38.610
In fact, an hour before this
event happens I bought a

00:05:38.610 --> 00:05:39.910
Japanese pressing

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:41.570
of Led Zeppelin IV right
in this record store.

00:05:41.570 --> 00:05:45.000
And I was actually
talking to the store owner

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.340
about what hydrology is.

00:05:46.340 --> 00:05:49.900
And I said, "Well, hydrology
is the study of water

00:05:49.900 --> 00:05:52.440
and the forecasting of
floods and droughts."

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:56.000
I saw him the next
day, gave him a hug.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:57.470
And he said, "Hydrology.

00:05:57.470 --> 00:06:00.560
I know what that is."

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:06.490
But a lot of people's lives
were uprooted from this event.

00:06:06.490 --> 00:06:07.790
Two people lost their lives.

00:06:07.790 --> 00:06:09.520
And a lot of people
were seriously injured.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:11.580
So it really brings it home.

00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:16.390
This is only a few miles
away in Ellicott City.

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:21.470
And on that note, roughly 90%

00:06:21.470 --> 00:06:25.500
of natural disasters
are related to water.

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:27.400
Okay? And, in fact,
water is now recognized

00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:30.540
as the number one threat
multiplier in the world.

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:33.360
So why is NASA interested
in water?

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:37.080
You know? It's because water
is used for agriculture.

00:06:37.080 --> 00:06:38.440
It's used for a lot of things.

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:40.040
Agriculture is a
global enterprise.

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:42.580
So the cost of wheat

00:06:42.580 --> 00:06:46.460
in the United States is directly
relevant to the productivity

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:49.970
of wheat in South
America or Central Asia.

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:51.270
Okay? So for that reason we need

00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:53.550
to set our sights a
little bit broader

00:06:53.550 --> 00:06:55.790
than just the United States.

00:06:55.790 --> 00:06:58.560
So on that note, this is one

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:01.060
of the most iconic
images ever taken.

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:03.240
Right? So this is
"The Blue Marble."

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:04.560
And it really is blue.

00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:08.110
Everything you see here
that's blue or white is water.

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:10.720
Right? And if you go down
through the numbers here,

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:13.490
and you think, "Well, let's
go back to junior high school.

00:07:13.490 --> 00:07:15.200
Let's go back to
the water cycle."

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:17.300
Right? It's pretty simple.

00:07:17.300 --> 00:07:20.700
Water falls from
clouds, precipitates.

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:22.650
Some of it is stored in snow,

00:07:22.650 --> 00:07:24.500
and some of it's
stored in glaciers.

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:26.390
Some of it runs down.

00:07:26.390 --> 00:07:29.070
It's stored in surface
water and in reservoirs

00:07:29.070 --> 00:07:30.740
and lakes and in streams.

00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:33.570
Some of it meets groundwater.

00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:35.710
It makes its way
back to the oceans.

00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:37.490
And, eventually,
evaporates up to clouds.

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:39.180
Right? Pretty simple.

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:43.860
So our challenge here is to,
as accurately as possible,

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:46.190
characterize, understand

00:07:46.190 --> 00:07:50.270
and predict each component
of this water cycle.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:55.720
Right? And from that we'll have
a better idea of how to assess

00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:58.560
and mitigate extreme
events like these floods

00:07:58.560 --> 00:08:02.280
and drought events
that are occurring.

00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:04.850
So, you know, we are
in "The Blue Marble."

00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:08.680
Right? Because over 70% of the
planet is covered by water.

00:08:08.680 --> 00:08:11.390
Right? However, only
a tiny portion,

00:08:11.390 --> 00:08:15.030
about 2.5% is fresh water.

00:08:15.030 --> 00:08:16.890
So it's a very small fraction.

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:22.930
In fact, of that 2.5% over
half of it is in glaciers.

00:08:22.930 --> 00:08:26.810
There's only a small
portion that is fresh water

00:08:26.810 --> 00:08:30.450
that is available to us through
surface water or ground water.

00:08:30.450 --> 00:08:32.180
Okay, and if you look
at that, okay, well,

00:08:32.180 --> 00:08:33.480
there's lots of water.

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:34.780
There's a little bit left.

00:08:34.780 --> 00:08:36.080
Where is that water going?

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:38.360
Most of its used
for agriculture.

00:08:38.360 --> 00:08:40.510
Right? And, so, this
is where, you know,

00:08:40.510 --> 00:08:42.720
with the Applied Sciences
Program at NASA we're looking

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:46.360
at innovative solutions
of monitoring water use.

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:48.100
You can actually
measure the amount

00:08:48.100 --> 00:08:51.030
of water that's being applied
and lost through plants.

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:57.820
So we can encourage people
to move from flood irrigation

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:02.000
to drip irrigation, more
efficient uses of water.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So I have a five-year-old
daughter.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:05.300
Her name's Lily [assumed
spelling].

00:09:05.300 --> 00:09:09.520
Right? By the time she's my age
there'll be roughly nine billion

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:10.820
people on the planet.

00:09:10.820 --> 00:09:13.600
When I was born there
was nearly four billion.

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:19.480
Okay? That's a pretty extreme
trend here we're seeing.

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:21.360
So the challenge is
how do we prepare

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:24.190
for this increased
population globally.

00:09:24.190 --> 00:09:26.420
What is their relationship
with water going to be?

00:09:26.420 --> 00:09:28.120
Is there enough water
to go around?

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:30.720
I'll tell you right now
there is enough water.

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:32.130
But if we look at
the distribution

00:09:32.130 --> 00:09:35.740
of the global population
density, we see some areas

00:09:35.740 --> 00:09:38.280
where there's a high population.

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:42.460
Right? And if we look at
a map of water stress,

00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:45.290
so simply the ratio
of water withdrawal

00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:48.960
to water availability, we
see in these similar areas,

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:50.930
the same areas we're
seeing with high population,

00:09:50.930 --> 00:09:52.770
there's high-water stress.

00:09:52.770 --> 00:09:56.730
So, in fact, a lot of the areas
that have water insecurity

00:09:56.730 --> 00:10:00.810
and food insecurity are these
areas with high population

00:10:00.810 --> 00:10:05.110
and future population
increases that are projected.

00:10:05.110 --> 00:10:06.940
So our challenge here is to find

00:10:06.940 --> 00:10:10.770
out how we can keep
what we have,

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:13.870
properly manage the
water that is available.

00:10:13.870 --> 00:10:18.550
Now a similar trend that we
see here, this is Moore's Law.

00:10:18.550 --> 00:10:21.430
Okay? And it, essentially, says
that every two years the number

00:10:21.430 --> 00:10:23.860
of transistors in a
circuit will double.

00:10:23.860 --> 00:10:27.630
Right? So my iPhone here,
if you look at this, oh,

00:10:27.630 --> 00:10:29.190
this was another quiz.

00:10:29.190 --> 00:10:30.890
Does anyone know what this is?

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:32.190
&gt;&gt; The ENIAC?

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:33.490
&gt;&gt; The ENIAC computer.

00:10:33.490 --> 00:10:35.100
Right. So this is in 1946.

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:38.220
This is considered the
first quote/unquote

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:39.880
"general-purpose computer."

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:44.750
Right? So my iPhone here
is 230 million times faster

00:10:44.750 --> 00:10:46.680
than the ENIAC computer.

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:48.690
And that's just 70 years ago.

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:52.390
So technology is advancing,

00:10:52.390 --> 00:10:55.150
population increase
is also advancing.

00:10:55.150 --> 00:10:57.710
So we have all kinds
of fancy tools and ways

00:10:57.710 --> 00:11:01.000
to measure different parts
of the global water cycle.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.490
Right? We can go out and
measure the amount of rainfall.

00:11:03.490 --> 00:11:06.210
Right? It's not rocket science.

00:11:06.210 --> 00:11:08.860
Okay? We can also
look at snow depth.

00:11:08.860 --> 00:11:10.160
This definitely isn't
rocket science.

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:12.740
They literally just
take a meter stick,

00:11:12.740 --> 00:11:15.020
and measure the amount of snow.

00:11:15.020 --> 00:11:18.160
But, in fact, if you look at,
let's see, San Joaquin Valley

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:22.100
in California, most of their
water is sourced by snowpack.

00:11:22.100 --> 00:11:24.860
Okay? So if they're going to
prepare for the amount of water

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:27.390
in the next season, they go
out, they get a bunch of people

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:28.700
where they go out and
use these meter sticks,

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:31.210
and they measure the
amount of snowpack.

00:11:31.210 --> 00:11:34.440
Okay? And from that they
derive a Snow Water Equivalent,

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:37.080
the amount of water
that's held in that.

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:39.890
And from that they can determine
how much water will be available

00:11:39.890 --> 00:11:41.190
next season.

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:43.470
Okay. You can also look at
how much water is evaporating

00:11:43.470 --> 00:11:46.550
from the land surface
and from plants

00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:48.790
through evapotranspiration.

00:11:48.790 --> 00:11:51.500
Okay? These are different
sensors of doing this.

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:53.520
You can also use something
called a "ThetaProbe," which,

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:56.800
essentially, measures
the electronic resistance

00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:58.100
of the soil.

00:11:58.100 --> 00:11:59.400
So the amount of water

00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:02.530
in the soil is measured
by this instrument.

00:12:02.530 --> 00:12:05.210
It gives you the
amount of soil moisture.

00:12:05.210 --> 00:12:07.070
You can also look at river flow.

00:12:07.070 --> 00:12:08.480
Okay? All these gauge stations,

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:10.600
all these in situ
datasets are great.

00:12:10.600 --> 00:12:12.700
And you can also
look at groundwater.

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:14.960
You can go out somewhere,
and you dig a well,

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:19.300
and you have an idea of
how much water there is.

00:12:19.300 --> 00:12:21.140
Now the problem with this is

00:12:21.140 --> 00:12:24.740
that ground stations
are expensive,

00:12:24.740 --> 00:12:27.930
and they are difficult
to maintain.

00:12:27.930 --> 00:12:30.150
And if you look at
just the distribution

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:32.790
in the United States, this
is groundwater, right,

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:34.420
Groundwater Climate
Response Network.

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:35.790
There's not many now.

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:37.680
There's not many
observations here.

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:40.860
If you look globally, this is
the Global Telecommunication

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:43.740
System, you can see
there's a lot of areas

00:12:43.740 --> 00:12:46.140
without a yellow dot on it.

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:50.320
And, so, the message here is
that ground data is expensive,

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:52.110
it's difficult to maintain.

00:12:52.110 --> 00:12:53.500
And especially when
you're concerned

00:12:53.500 --> 00:13:00.030
about transboundary aquifers and
crossing political boundaries,

00:13:00.030 --> 00:13:01.910
it's very difficult
to share data.

00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:04.220
You know, you can have my
data, but you can't have it.

00:13:04.220 --> 00:13:06.260
I can have it, but I'm not
going to give it to this guy.

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:07.560
It's a huge issue.

00:13:07.560 --> 00:13:09.910
But when you're dealing with a
watershed, when you're dealing

00:13:09.910 --> 00:13:13.040
with a resource that's
common to everyone,

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:17.620
you need this common sharing
of water and water data.

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:23.720
So going back also to 1946,
this is October 26, 1946.

00:13:23.720 --> 00:13:26.790
This is the first image ever
taken of the planet Earth.

00:13:26.790 --> 00:13:31.290
Some scientists launched
a Delta II rocket

00:13:31.290 --> 00:13:34.950
from the White Sands Air
Force Base in California.

00:13:34.950 --> 00:13:37.340
And they were lucky
enough to get this picture.

00:13:37.340 --> 00:13:41.040
And initially they were all
concerned about the clouds.

00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:43.000
They're like, "Oh,
these clouds are,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:44.350
you know, messing up our view."

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:47.930
But, in fact, we know now
that's really what we're after.

00:13:47.930 --> 00:13:51.330
So if we go back
again to junior high,

00:13:51.330 --> 00:13:52.630
the electromagnetic spectrum.

00:13:52.630 --> 00:13:58.040
Right? So our eyes
capture the ambient light.

00:13:58.040 --> 00:14:00.030
We see colors.

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:04.010
These colors, in fact, are
only a very small fraction

00:14:04.010 --> 00:14:07.170
of the total electromagnetic
spectrum.

00:14:07.170 --> 00:14:09.310
Right? We're only
seeing a little bit.

00:14:09.310 --> 00:14:11.370
So all this energy's
down from the sun.

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:14.920
Some of it's reflected
through visible light.

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:17.380
Some of it is reflected
through x-rays

00:14:17.380 --> 00:14:21.350
and ultraviolet microwaves
and radio waves.

00:14:21.350 --> 00:14:26.700
So we can use these other parts
of the electromagnetic spectrum

00:14:26.700 --> 00:14:29.640
to assess parts of the
global water cycle.

00:14:29.640 --> 00:14:36.560
A tree looks very different
in infrared or near frared

00:14:36.560 --> 00:14:38.280
than it does in visible light.

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:41.490
In fact, it tells us
different information

00:14:41.490 --> 00:14:43.200
than the visible light.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:45.580
So we get beautiful pictures
like this, but we're also able

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:48.970
to look at not only is the
tree green, is it yellow,

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:52.590
but is it healthy, is its
senescing, is it growing,

00:14:52.590 --> 00:14:54.800
how much water is it using.

00:14:54.800 --> 00:14:57.870
So we can also use
different parts

00:14:57.870 --> 00:15:00.660
of the electromagnetic
spectrum, like microwaves,

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:04.960
which are correlated with the
amount of moisture in soil.

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:08.650
So we're combining all these
different technologies trying

00:15:08.650 --> 00:15:11.440
to tell that story of
the water landscape

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:13.680
at that global water
cycle, different components,

00:15:13.680 --> 00:15:16.580
each different component,
how can we measure

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:19.170
and predict each part.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:24.610
So if you fast forward to 2018,
NASA has a whole constellation

00:15:24.610 --> 00:15:28.490
of satellites that utilize
different components

00:15:28.490 --> 00:15:31.930
of the electromagnetic
spectrum for focusing

00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:36.250
and monitoring different
components of the water cycle.

00:15:36.250 --> 00:15:37.830
And we're also collaborating

00:15:37.830 --> 00:15:39.680
with the International
Space Station.

00:15:39.680 --> 00:15:42.900
We have instruments
there that stay on for

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:44.620
about one to three years.

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:47.810
And what's unique about the
ISS is it has a slightly

00:15:47.810 --> 00:15:49.160
unique orbit.

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:50.460
So it captures things

00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:53.070
that aren't captured
by other satellites.

00:15:53.070 --> 00:15:59.120
So the whole idea is, let's
see, as frequently as possible

00:15:59.120 --> 00:16:01.390
and as accurately as possible,

00:16:01.390 --> 00:16:04.240
monitor different parts
of that water cycle.

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:07.020
So I'm going to show
a few examples

00:16:07.020 --> 00:16:09.870
of what we're seeing from space.

00:16:09.870 --> 00:16:13.750
This is one of NASA's recently
launched satellites called the

00:16:13.750 --> 00:16:17.120
"Global Precipitation
Measurement Mission," GPM.

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:19.670
So instead of just having a
few gauges all over, you know,

00:16:19.670 --> 00:16:23.880
we can now have every 30
minutes on the planet,

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:26.370
we have an estimate
of precipitation.

00:16:26.370 --> 00:16:29.590
Right? Not just over land,
but over sea as well.

00:16:29.590 --> 00:16:35.740
And this is extremely powerful
if your business is hydrology,

00:16:35.740 --> 00:16:42.240
okay, and figuring out where
the water is and where it isn't.

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:46.190
Another satellite that is
widely used is "MODIS."

00:16:46.190 --> 00:16:50.510
It's the Moderate Resolution
Imaging Spectroradiometer.

00:16:50.510 --> 00:16:53.690
And what's really neat about
this is you see this sort

00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:56.010
of pulsing, this
breathing of the planet.

00:16:56.010 --> 00:16:59.950
And you see it growing and
senescing of vegetation.

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:03.890
Right? And this is
sped up, obviously,

00:17:03.890 --> 00:17:07.670
but through MODIS we get
frequent observations

00:17:07.670 --> 00:17:10.270
of vegetation health.

00:17:10.270 --> 00:17:13.780
And this is one of the
most widely used satellites

00:17:13.780 --> 00:17:15.640
that NASA has.

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:19.670
A couple missions that
are up and coming,

00:17:19.670 --> 00:17:21.390
about to be launched,
are exciting.

00:17:21.390 --> 00:17:23.760
One of them is called "ICESat."

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:28.740
And this is using Lidar,
or laser altimetry.

00:17:28.740 --> 00:17:30.190
And think about this.

00:17:30.190 --> 00:17:33.970
From space, from several
hundred kilometers up,

00:17:33.970 --> 00:17:39.590
you can detect the height
of water or a glacier

00:17:39.590 --> 00:17:42.320
with an accuracy of centimeters.

00:17:42.320 --> 00:17:46.290
Okay? This is a highly
anticipated mission,

00:17:46.290 --> 00:17:48.740
as well as the Surface
Water Ocean Topography,

00:17:48.740 --> 00:17:50.640
or SWOT, Mission.

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:52.730
This uses a slightly
different technology.

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:56.590
It's a synthetic aperture
radar interferometric system.

00:17:56.590 --> 00:18:00.960
I was nervous about
saying that, but I did it.

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:05.930
But the idea here is to measure
the topography of the ocean,

00:18:05.930 --> 00:18:11.450
of the ocean surface and also
the rivers and reservoirs.

00:18:11.450 --> 00:18:16.160
So I just find it pretty
amazing to think from hundreds

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:19.420
of kilometers up you're able to
tell the height of a reservoir

00:18:19.420 --> 00:18:22.420
or lake, or even a river, within
the accuracy of centimeters.

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:24.620
That's pretty wild.

00:18:24.620 --> 00:18:27.230
One of my favorite missions
I talk about is "GRACE."

00:18:27.230 --> 00:18:31.010
It's stands for the Gravity
Recovery and Climate Experiment.

00:18:31.010 --> 00:18:33.570
And there's a follow-on
mission to be launched here

00:18:33.570 --> 00:18:36.670
in about the next month, a
GRACE II, or a GRACE follow-on.

00:18:36.670 --> 00:18:38.910
But what makes GRACE unique?

00:18:38.910 --> 00:18:42.060
It's not a satellite
looking down at the earth.

00:18:42.060 --> 00:18:46.250
In fact, it's two
satellites flying in tandem

00:18:46.250 --> 00:18:47.550
that are looking at each other.

00:18:47.550 --> 00:18:49.230
They're not looking down.

00:18:49.230 --> 00:18:50.530
So they're looking
at each other.

00:18:50.530 --> 00:18:53.340
Right? They're looking
at each other,

00:18:53.340 --> 00:18:56.530
and they're measuring
this horizontal distance

00:18:56.530 --> 00:18:58.870
within the accuracy
of one red blood cell,

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:00.170
if you can believe that.

00:19:00.170 --> 00:19:04.360
Right? So if there's a mountain
or a large landmass here,

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:07.230
that first satellite will be
pulled forward just slightly.

00:19:07.230 --> 00:19:09.560
And this horizontal
distance will change.

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:14.330
Okay? And they keep on doing
that, they go around the planet,

00:19:14.330 --> 00:19:15.630
go around and go around.

00:19:15.630 --> 00:19:17.700
And what they're doing
is they're mapping the

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:21.990
gravitational pull of the earth,
of the different land masses.

00:19:21.990 --> 00:19:23.910
And a change from one month

00:19:23.910 --> 00:19:27.330
to the next is a
gravitational anomaly.

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:29.580
Now mountains really
don't move that quickly.

00:19:29.580 --> 00:19:33.500
So if you see a large anomaly,
you can infer a movement

00:19:33.500 --> 00:19:35.800
of water, because
water has mass.

00:19:35.800 --> 00:19:38.000
And, so, in fact, what
you're seeing here,

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.060
these different colors
are the terrestrial water

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:43.730
storage anomalies.

00:19:43.730 --> 00:19:46.720
And this was really a game
changer for hydrology,

00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:50.470
because we're always trying
to solve the water budget for

00:19:50.470 --> 00:19:52.160
"our residual is
always groundwater."

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:53.970
You know, what's
the Delta storage?

00:19:53.970 --> 00:19:55.350
What's the change in storage?

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:57.020
Well, now we have a
direct observation

00:19:57.020 --> 00:19:59.340
of that change in storage.

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:06.840
And it's a truly novel satellite
mission launched by NASA.

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:09.000
Now this is really cool.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.370
First of all, I think that Bob
Ross would probably be super

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:13.180
jealous of the happy
clouds here.

00:20:13.180 --> 00:20:16.460
Because what you see, all this
is is two satellite observations

00:20:16.460 --> 00:20:17.780
laid over each other.

00:20:17.780 --> 00:20:21.800
So you have a satellite-based
soil moisture observation shown

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:23.470
here in blue and orange.

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:25.650
These are soil moisture
anomalies.

00:20:25.650 --> 00:20:30.280
And the yellow and red
are GPM precipitation.

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:31.750
Right? It kind of makes sense.

00:20:31.750 --> 00:20:34.260
Where it rains the
soil gets wet.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:39.600
Right? But it's really useful
for helping convey this concept

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:41.390
of precipitation memory.

00:20:41.390 --> 00:20:43.570
Where is it raining
and where is it not?

00:20:43.570 --> 00:20:46.450
Where is the water
holding water,

00:20:46.450 --> 00:20:48.770
or where is the soil holding
water, where is it not?

00:20:48.770 --> 00:20:52.600
And it's become a pretty
cool educational tool.

00:20:52.600 --> 00:20:56.360
But it also is really useful
for just showing the utility

00:20:56.360 --> 00:20:58.790
of combining multiple
datasets from satellite,

00:20:58.790 --> 00:21:01.420
and helping tell this story

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:05.280
of the global water
cycle more completely.

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:11.050
So back to the water cycle.

00:21:11.050 --> 00:21:12.350
All right.

00:21:12.350 --> 00:21:13.650
So we have all these
different observations.

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:14.950
We're sensing precipitation.

00:21:14.950 --> 00:21:18.960
We can detect rivers and
reservoirs, and all this stuff.

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:20.700
Okay? But what do
you do with it?

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:23.170
Well, where the rubber
meets the road really is

00:21:23.170 --> 00:21:26.870
through numerical modeling
and land surface modeling.

00:21:26.870 --> 00:21:31.180
And all that is is an
estimation of reality.

00:21:31.180 --> 00:21:36.230
Right? It's based on physical
equations that are, hopefully,

00:21:36.230 --> 00:21:37.900
physically consistent.

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:40.610
You're trying to mimic
what you see in nature.

00:21:40.610 --> 00:21:44.110
You're trying to mimic if a
certain temperature and pressure

00:21:44.110 --> 00:21:46.820
in this cloud, when will
it precipitate water.

00:21:46.820 --> 00:21:48.820
Right? It kind of makes sense.

00:21:48.820 --> 00:21:51.990
A lot of these equations have
been derived in laboratories.

00:21:51.990 --> 00:21:53.840
And then they're applied

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:56.360
to real-world applications
like we see here.

00:21:56.360 --> 00:21:58.680
So we have all kinds
of different equations,

00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:02.170
numerical models that we
integrate these observations

00:22:02.170 --> 00:22:04.800
of satellite, we take
these observations

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:08.130
of in situ observations and
gauge data, and we just try

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:10.850
to tell that story more
completely in a way

00:22:10.850 --> 00:22:12.700
that is physically consistent

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:15.220
and makes sense and
that we can use.

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:17.700
And when you understand
what's happening now,

00:22:17.700 --> 00:22:20.580
you have a better idea of
what's going to happen tomorrow.

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:22.870
And that's what it
all boils down to.

00:22:22.870 --> 00:22:25.570
So back to "The Blue Marble."

00:22:25.570 --> 00:22:27.800
Where are we?

00:22:27.800 --> 00:22:30.790
So it's something that I
think most people are familiar

00:22:30.790 --> 00:22:32.910
with is the drought
that occurred

00:22:32.910 --> 00:22:35.990
in California a couple
years ago.

00:22:35.990 --> 00:22:37.290
So if you just look

00:22:37.290 --> 00:22:40.230
at the terrestrial water
storage changes in California

00:22:40.230 --> 00:22:43.910
from the GRACE satellite,
and you can see here,

00:22:43.910 --> 00:22:46.370
what we're seeing, there's
a little red dot that goes.

00:22:46.370 --> 00:22:50.650
And you can see this trend,
a significant decrease

00:22:50.650 --> 00:22:53.150
in terrestrial water storage.

00:22:53.150 --> 00:22:55.480
And, again, it repeats.

00:22:55.480 --> 00:22:58.500
And this made a lot of headlines
in the news, because, for one,

00:22:58.500 --> 00:23:00.810
it's very easy to
see, "Okay red is bad.

00:23:00.810 --> 00:23:02.250
Blue is good."

00:23:02.250 --> 00:23:04.530
You know, California,
it's going down.

00:23:04.530 --> 00:23:06.110
But what it did is
help tell part

00:23:06.110 --> 00:23:09.970
of that water landscape
story for California.

00:23:13.470 --> 00:23:17.910
Now if we go back to Cape Town,
right, so let's say, "Oh, yeah,

00:23:17.910 --> 00:23:19.820
Cape Town, it says they're
going to run out of water.

00:23:19.820 --> 00:23:21.590
They're experiencing a drought."

00:23:21.590 --> 00:23:23.880
Okay. Well, what does that mean?

00:23:23.880 --> 00:23:25.930
How can water managers
there prepare?

00:23:25.930 --> 00:23:27.850
What are they going to do?

00:23:27.850 --> 00:23:29.150
Is it really a drought?

00:23:29.150 --> 00:23:30.450
And how extensive will it be?

00:23:30.450 --> 00:23:32.070
And how long will it last?

00:23:32.070 --> 00:23:33.410
You know? What happens?

00:23:33.410 --> 00:23:35.730
So the first thing they do is
you look at the climatology,

00:23:35.730 --> 00:23:39.170
which is, essentially, just a
long-term record of weather.

00:23:39.170 --> 00:23:42.710
And, you know, every area
has this unique climatology.

00:23:42.710 --> 00:23:46.310
So this is what's happened in
the past, and what is it going

00:23:46.310 --> 00:23:50.160
to look like today or
tomorrow or next year.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:55.790
So we use numerical modeling
to look at seasonal forecasts.

00:23:55.790 --> 00:24:00.240
Okay? And you say, "Okay, well,
what may it look like in May

00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:05.110
to July of 2018, all the way
up to September, October 2018?"

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:06.410
It's very similar.

00:24:06.410 --> 00:24:07.710
In fact, it's the same
thing you see when you turn

00:24:07.710 --> 00:24:09.170
on the Weather Channel.

00:24:09.170 --> 00:24:12.290
Right? Those are
short-term forecasts.

00:24:12.290 --> 00:24:13.770
Well, there's long-term
forecasts as well,

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:15.510
but they're all based
on the same thing.

00:24:15.510 --> 00:24:19.800
You need accurate observations
to initialize those models.

00:24:19.800 --> 00:24:22.540
And you're providing
estimates, in this case,

00:24:22.540 --> 00:24:27.550
of a future climatology, or
future forecasts of the weather.

00:24:27.550 --> 00:24:30.170
So what does soil moisture
look like in Cape Town?

00:24:30.170 --> 00:24:33.100
And how is that related
to the drought?

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:36.250
Well, the whole idea is
having a long-term record,

00:24:36.250 --> 00:24:40.360
have a historical perspective
of all of these variables

00:24:40.360 --> 00:24:42.060
of the global water cycle.

00:24:42.060 --> 00:24:45.420
So we see here, if we look at
an anomaly of soil moisture,

00:24:45.420 --> 00:24:48.020
we can look at this year's
soil moisture compared

00:24:48.020 --> 00:24:49.320
to last year's.

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:51.540
It's very straightforward,
very simple for that point.

00:24:51.540 --> 00:24:55.740
But then if you isolate
different areas, in this case,

00:24:55.740 --> 00:25:00.400
of southern Africa that are
used for agriculture, well,

00:25:00.400 --> 00:25:02.250
soil moisture is a
leading indicator

00:25:02.250 --> 00:25:04.350
of agriculture, of drought.

00:25:04.350 --> 00:25:06.990
Right? So we say that
the soil moisture now,

00:25:06.990 --> 00:25:11.080
the soil moisture anomaly we
have now is a leading indicator

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:14.640
of vegetation next
month or next week.

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:16.330
So we use this as a way

00:25:16.330 --> 00:25:18.860
of forecasting future
agricultural drought.

00:25:18.860 --> 00:25:20.650
In fact, the definition

00:25:20.650 --> 00:25:23.710
of agricultural drought is
the deficit of soil moisture.

00:25:23.710 --> 00:25:25.820
Soil moisture's dear
to my heart.

00:25:25.820 --> 00:25:27.760
I've been studying it for years.

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:32.490
And it's turned out to be one
of the most important variables

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:34.520
in hydrology, because
it's a boundary condition

00:25:34.520 --> 00:25:37.010
between the land surface
and the atmosphere.

00:25:37.010 --> 00:25:39.790
Just like your body, when you
get hot, your body sweats.

00:25:39.790 --> 00:25:42.660
