moisture a lot.

00:56:57.820 --> 00:57:00.530
And if I have one or two
years of soil moisture,

00:57:00.530 --> 00:57:02.900
I'm not really going to be able

00:57:02.900 --> 00:57:05.900
to derive a reliable
anomaly from that.

00:57:05.900 --> 00:57:09.700
Okay? But if I have ten
years, maybe I will.

00:57:09.700 --> 00:57:13.280
The idea with soil
moisture related

00:57:13.280 --> 00:57:16.230
to agriculture is you want to
see several growing seasons.

00:57:16.230 --> 00:57:20.400
And you want to capture extremes
in those growing seasons,

00:57:20.400 --> 00:57:21.870
and extremes in that hydrology.

00:57:21.870 --> 00:57:25.120
If you're looking at flooding,
you want to see a year

00:57:25.120 --> 00:57:27.060
that was at an extreme.

00:57:27.060 --> 00:57:28.710
You would want to see
a year that was also

00:57:28.710 --> 00:57:31.580
at a very low extreme,
so you can capture those.

00:57:31.580 --> 00:57:37.880
And when you do that,
you have a better sense.

00:57:37.880 --> 00:57:41.610
The lifespan of NASA satellite
missions are all unique.

00:57:41.610 --> 00:57:43.880
But I think to be conservative
they throw them up there

00:57:43.880 --> 00:57:45.990
to be roughly three
to five years.

00:57:45.990 --> 00:57:51.760
But many satellites have
lasted longer than ten.

00:57:51.760 --> 00:57:55.360
